\begin{document}

\maketitle

\begin{abstract}
    Environmental monitoring of anthropogenic stressors is typically fragmented, treating different pollutants within isolated frameworks. This separation obscures critical interactions and limits monitoring efficiency. We propose a unified geo-ecological information-modeling system (\gims) that integrates the quantification of artificial light at night (\alan) as an anthropogenic photon volume concentration with hydro-chemical water pollution monitoring. Our novel contribution is threefold: (1) the integration of a photon concentration conversion module within the \gims architecture, enabling \alan to be treated as a standard atmospheric pollutant; (2) the formulation of a joint optimization objective for sparse sensor network design that simultaneously minimizes uncertainty in predicting both photon and water pollutant concentrations; and (3) the development of a coupled prediction model that accounts for light-water interactions. We present the complete mathematical framework, detailing the conversion from traditional photometric quantities to photon concentrations and the joint monitoring optimization algorithm. An experimental plan for validation is outlined, using a multi-modal dataset to test the hypothesis that the integrated system achieves ≥15\% reduction in combined prediction error compared to separate monitoring regimes, while maintaining accuracy with 50\% fewer sensors. This work establishes a foundation for physically consistent, economically efficient monitoring of coupled anthropogenic stressors in sensitive coastal ecosystems.

    \textbf{Keywords:} Geo-ecological information modeling, light pollution, photon concentration, sensor network optimization, water quality monitoring, coupled systems
\end{abstract}

\section{Introduction}
Anthropogenic activities have introduced diverse pollutants into atmospheric and aquatic systems, threatening ecosystem integrity and human health. Among these, artificial light at night (\alan) has emerged as a pervasive pollutant disrupting nocturnal environments, while hydro-chemical contamination of water bodies remains a critical challenge. Current environmental monitoring paradigms treat these stressors separately, employing distinct metrics and frameworks. Light pollution is conventionally described via photometric quantities (luminance, illuminance) tied to human vision, framing it as exceptional rather than as a standard air pollutant. Conversely, water quality monitoring often relies on resource-intensive, periodic in-situ measurements that may be spatially and temporally inadequate.

This separation misses critical ecological interactions—for instance, how \alan affects near-shore biogeochemistry or predator-prey dynamics—and fails to leverage potential synergies in monitoring optimization. The Geo-ecological Information-Modeling System (\gims) \cite{gims_paper} demonstrates efficacy in optimizing water quality monitoring through simulation-observation synergy but does not incorporate novel pollutant quantifications like photon concentration. Simultaneously, the photon concentration framework \cite{photon_paper} provides a rigorous physical description of \alan as a volume concentration of photons, aligning it with conventional air pollution metrics, yet lacks an integrated system for operational monitoring.

We bridge this gap by developing an integrated \gims framework that quantifies both \alan (as anthropogenic photon volume concentration) and hydro-chemical water pollution within a single, adaptive monitoring and modeling system. The core idea is to use the photon concentration framework to treat \alan as a standard atmospheric pollutant and the \gims architecture to dynamically optimize a sparse sensor network for monitoring the coupled air-water pollution state in coastal environments.

The primary research objectives are:
\begin{enumerate}
    \item To formally integrate photon concentration conversion equations into the \gims architecture.
    \item To develop a joint optimization algorithm for sparse sensor placement that minimizes combined uncertainty in photon and water pollutant predictions.
    \item To validate the framework's efficacy in reducing prediction error and sensor costs compared to separate monitoring systems.
\end{enumerate}

This paper is structured as follows: \Cref{sec:related} reviews related work on light pollution quantification and environmental monitoring optimization. \Cref{sec:methodology} details the unified methodology, including the photon concentration module and joint optimization formulation. \Cref{sec:experiments} presents the experimental plan for validation. \Cref{sec:discussion} discusses anticipated implications and limitations, and \Cref{sec:conclusion} concludes with future research directions.

\section{Related Work}\label{sec:related}
\subsection{Light Pollution Quantification}
Traditionally, light pollution has been assessed using photometric quantities (e.g., illuminance in lux, luminance in cd/m²) derived from human visual response \cite{cinzano2001}. While useful for lighting design, this surface-flux-based approach conceptually separates light from classical air pollutants, which are standardly expressed as volume concentrations (e.g., µg/m³ for PM2.5). Recent work by \cite{photon_paper} reframes \alan as the volume concentration of anthropogenic photons, deriving explicit conversion equations from radiometric quantities. This formulation treats light as a physical entity propagating through the atmosphere, enabling direct comparison with other airborne contaminants and providing a more fundamental metric for environmental and health impact studies.

\subsection{Environmental Monitoring Optimization}
Optimizing environmental monitoring networks is a well-studied problem. The \gims framework \cite{gims_paper} combines numerical simulation models with observational data to optimize sensor placement in aquatic systems using statistical decision procedures (NPS/SAP). It reduces monitoring costs while maintaining prediction accuracy. Similar approaches exist in air quality monitoring \cite{liu2018}. However, these systems are typically pollutant-specific and do not address the joint optimization of multiple, potentially interacting pollutant classes.

\subsection{Integrated Monitoring Frameworks}
Some studies attempt multi-pollutant monitoring. For instance, \cite{smith2020} used a coupled atmospheric-hydrological model to study nutrient deposition. However, light pollution is consistently omitted from such integrated assessments. The conceptual separation of light as a pollutant has hindered its inclusion in holistic environmental management frameworks. Our work directly addresses this gap by providing the mathematical and architectural basis for unified monitoring.

\section{Methodology}\label{sec:methodology}
The proposed unified framework consists of three core components: (1) a Photon Concentration Module, (2) a Coupled Prediction Model, and (3) a Joint Observational Optimization Engine, all embedded within the \gims architecture.

\subsection{Photon Concentration Module}
We adopt the photon concentration framework from \cite{photon_paper}. The fundamental conversion relates spectral radiance $\radiance(\alpha)$ (W·m$^{-2}$·sr$^{-1}$·nm$^{-1}$) to spectral photon volume concentration $\photonlambda(\alpha)$ (photons·m$^{-3}$·nm$^{-1}$):
\begin{equation}\label{eq:photon_lambda}
    \photonlambda(\alpha) = \frac{\radiance(\alpha)}{h \nu \cdot c \cdot \cos z},
\end{equation}
where $h$ is Planck's constant, $\nu$ is frequency, $c$ is the speed of light, and $z$ is the angle between the propagation direction and the surface normal.

The total band-weighted photon concentration $\photon$ for a normalized spectral sensitivity function $\Lambda(\lambda)$ (e.g., CIE $V_\lambda$) is:
\begin{equation}\label{eq:total_photon}
    \photon = \int_{\lambda} \int_{\Omega} \Lambda(\lambda) \cdot \photonlambda(\alpha) \cdot \cos z \, d\Omega \, d\lambda.
\end{equation}

A key practical conversion constant $\muv$ links illuminance $E_v$ (in lux) to photopic photon concentration:
\begin{equation}\label{eq:muV}
    \muv = \frac{K_{cd}}{K_0 \cdot h\nu \cdot c} \approx 1.3590 \times 10^7 \text{ photons·m}^{-3}\text{ per lx},
\end{equation}
where $K_{cd}=683$ lm/W is the photopic luminous efficacy and $K_0=1$ photons/(W·s) is a unit conversion constant. Thus, $\photon = \muv \cdot E_v$.

This module is implemented as a pre-processing step, converting raw light intensity measurements (lux) from sensors or satellite-derived radiance data into photon concentration maps.

\subsection{Coupled Prediction Model}
The system state at location $\mathbf{x}$ and time $t$ is represented by a vector $\mathbf{Y}_t(\mathbf{x}) = [\photon_t(\mathbf{x}), \mathbf{W}_t(\mathbf{x})]^\top$, where $\mathbf{W}$ represents water quality parameters (e.g., dissolved oxygen, nutrients). We develop a coupled dynamical model:
\begin{align}
    \hat{\photon}_t &= f_\theta(\mathbf{X}_{\text{geo}}, \mathbf{X}_{\text{meteo}}, t; \Theta_f), \label{eq:light_model} \\
    \hat{\mathbf{W}}_t &= g_\phi(\mathbf{X}_{\text{geo}}, \mathbf{X}_{\text{hydro}}, \hat{\photon}_t, t; \Theta_g), \label{eq:water_model}
\end{align}
where $f_\theta$ and $g_\phi$ are parameterized functions (e.g., neural networks, Gaussian processes), $\mathbf{X}_{*}$ denote geographic, meteorological, and hydrological covariates, and $\Theta$ are learnable parameters. The coupling in \cref{eq:water_model} allows water quality predictions to be informed by light pollution levels, modeling potential indirect effects (e.g., altered phytoplankton activity).

\subsection{Joint Observational Optimization}
Let $\mathcal{S}$ denote a set of potential sensor locations, each capable of measuring either photon concentration, water quality parameters, or both, with associated costs. The optimization objective is to select a subset $\mathcal{S}^* \subset \mathcal{S}$ with total cost $\leq B$ that minimizes the combined prediction uncertainty:
\begin{equation}\label{eq:joint_opt}
    \min_{\mathcal{S}} \left[ \alpha \cdot \text{MSE}_{\photon}(\mathcal{S}) + \beta \cdot \text{MSE}_{\mathbf{W}}(\mathcal{S}) + \gamma \cdot \text{Cost}(\mathcal{S}) \right],
\end{equation}
subject to $\mathcal{S} \in \mathcal{F}, |\mathcal{S}| \leq B$, where $\mathcal{F}$ represents feasibility constraints (e.g., sensor compatibility, deployment logistics), and $\alpha, \beta, \gamma$ are weighting coefficients.

The mean squared error (MSE) terms are estimated via the \gims procedure: a numerical simulator (e.g., a hydrodynamic-ecological model for water, an atmospheric radiative transfer model for light) is run to generate a prior state estimate. The expected posterior uncertainty after assimilating measurements from $\mathcal{S}$ is computed using an ensemble Kalman filter or similar data assimilation technique. The optimization is solved using greedy algorithms or Bayesian optimization, guided by the \gims statistical decision modules.

An adaptive sampling criterion based on information gain $\Delta I$ is used for dynamic sensor scheduling:
\begin{equation}\label{eq:info_gain}
    \Delta I(\mathbf{x}_t) = H[\hat{\mathbf{Y}}_t(\mathbf{x})] - H[\hat{\mathbf{Y}}_{t-1}(\mathbf{x})],
\end{equation}
where $H[p] = -\sum p \log p$ is the entropy of the predictive distribution. Locations with high $\Delta I$ are prioritized for measurement.

The complete algorithm for one optimization cycle is outlined in \cref{alg:main}.

\begin{algorithm}[H]
\caption{Unified \gims Optimization Cycle}
\label{alg:main}
\begin{algorithmic}[1]
\STATE \textbf{Input:} Prior models $f_\theta, g_\phi$, candidate sensor set $\mathcal{S}$, budget $B$, weights $\alpha, \beta, \gamma$.
\STATE \textbf{Output:} Optimal sensor subset $\mathcal{S}^*$.
\STATE
\STATE \textbf{Step 1: Photon Conversion} \hfill \textit{(Module 1)}
\STATE Convert all historical light intensity data to $\photon$ using \cref{eq:muV}.
\STATE
\STATE \textbf{Step 2: Coupled Simulation} \hfill \textit{(Module 2)}
\STATE Run coupled simulator to generate prior state estimate $\hat{\mathbf{Y}}_t^{(0)}$ over the spatial grid.
\STATE
\STATE \textbf{Step 3: Uncertainty Quantification}
\STATE Compute prior uncertainty covariance $\mathbf{P}_t^{(0)}$.
\STATE
\STATE \textbf{Step 4: Sensor Selection} \hfill \textit{(Module 3)}
\FOR{each candidate sensor $s \in \mathcal{S}$}
    \STATE Compute expected posterior uncertainty $\mathbf{P}_t^{(s)}$ after assimilating measurement from $s$.
    \STATE Compute objective value $J(s)$ using \cref{eq:joint_opt}.
\ENDFOR
\STATE Select $\mathcal{S}^* = \arg\min_{\mathcal{S}' \subset \mathcal{S}, \text{Cost}(\mathcal{S}') \leq B} \sum_{s \in \mathcal{S}'} J(s)$.
\STATE
\STATE \textbf{Step 5: Measurement \& Assimilation}
\STATE Deploy sensors at $\mathcal{S}^*$, collect measurements $\mathbf{Z}_t$.
\STATE Assimilate $\mathbf{Z}_t$ to update state to $\hat{\mathbf{Y}}_t^{(1)}$ and covariance to $\mathbf{P}_t^{(1)}$.
\STATE
\STATE \textbf{Step 6: Adaptive Scheduling}
\STATE Compute information gain $\Delta I$ for all grid cells using \cref{eq:info_gain}.
\STATE If $\max(\Delta I) > \tau$, trigger re-optimization for next time step.
\end{algorithmic}
\end{algorithm}

\section{Experimental Plan}\label{sec:experiments}
To validate the proposed framework, we outline a comprehensive experimental plan. As complete results are not yet available, this section details the design, datasets, and evaluation protocols.

\subsection{Datasets}
The primary dataset is derived from a Kaggle repository containing water and air quality measurements across multiple cities \cite{kaggle_dataset}. The dataset includes 3,963 records with spatial coordinates, air quality index, and water pollution index. For our purposes, the air quality index column will be treated as a proxy for light intensity (lux), acknowledging this as a simplifying assumption for validation. Future work will use dedicated radiometric measurements.

\textbf{Preprocessing:} The light intensity values are converted to photon concentration $\photon$ using \cref{eq:muV}. Water quality parameters are normalized. The data is structured into a spatiotemporal grid with 100m resolution and hourly timesteps (synthetic timestamps are generated where missing).

\subsection{Baseline Models}
We establish two separate baseline monitoring systems:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Light-only \gims:} Optimizes sensor placement for photon concentration prediction only.
    \item \textbf{Water-only \gims:} Optimizes sensor placement for water quality prediction only.
\end{itemize}
Each baseline uses the standard \gims optimization \cite{gims_paper} with a single-objective version of \cref{eq:joint_opt}.

\subsection{Evaluation Metrics}
The integrated framework is evaluated against the baselines using:
\begin{enumerate}
    \item \textbf{Prediction Accuracy:} Combined $R^2$ and Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE) for both $\photon$ and $\mathbf{W}$ predictions on a held-out test set.
    \item \textbf{Optimization Efficiency:} Percentage reduction in combined prediction error compared to baselines, using the same sensor budget $B$.
    \item \textbf{Sensor Sparsity:} Prediction accuracy maintained when using 50\% fewer sensors than a dense reference network.
    \item \textbf{Computational Cost:} Runtime for one complete optimization cycle on a 1000×1000 grid.
\end{enumerate}

\subsection{Validation Protocol}
The experimental pipeline follows five phases:
\begin{enumerate}
    \item \textbf{Data Preparation \& Photon Conversion} (Module: \texttt{data\_preprocessor.py})
    \item \textbf{Baseline Establishment} (Module: \texttt{baseline\_models.py})
    \item \textbf{Integrated Framework Implementation} (Module: \texttt{integrated\_gims.py})
    \item \textbf{Optimization \& Validation} (Module: \texttt{optimization\_engine.py})
    \item \textbf{Ablation Studies} (Module: \texttt{ablation\_studies.py})
\end{enumerate}

We employ 5-fold cross-validation, temporal hold-out (last 30 days), and spatial hold-out (20\% random locations). Statistical significance of improvements is tested using paired t-tests ($p < 0.05$).

\subsection{Expected Results}
We anticipate the integrated framework will:
\begin{itemize}
    \item Achieve $\geq 15\%$ reduction in combined prediction error (MSE) compared to separate systems.
    \item Maintain prediction accuracy ($R^2 \geq 0.85$) with 50\% fewer sensors.
    \item Complete optimization cycles within 30 minutes on an 8-core CPU.
    \item Demonstrate that the photon concentration conversion is accurate (RMSE $\leq 0.1$ log units against theoretical calculations).
\end{itemize}

\section{Discussion}\label{sec:discussion}
The proposed unified framework represents a paradigm shift in environmental monitoring. By quantifying \alan as a photon concentration, it bridges a conceptual divide, allowing light pollution to be incorporated into standard air quality management frameworks. The joint optimization approach leverages synergies between monitoring different pollutants, potentially reducing costs and increasing the informational value of each measurement.

\subsection{Anticipated Implications}
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Scientific:} Provides a physically consistent metric for cross-disciplinary studies of light pollution impacts on aquatic ecosystems.
    \item \textbf{Managerial:} Offers a decision-support tool for designing cost-effective, multi-purpose monitoring networks in coastal zones.
    \item \textbf{Policy:} Facilitates the establishment of regulatory standards for \alan based on volume concentration, analogous to air quality standards.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Limitations and Challenges}
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Data Constraints:} The current validation uses a proxy dataset. Real-world deployment requires coordinated measurements of radiometric and water quality data.
    \item \textbf{Model Coupling Strength:} The empirical coupling between $\photon$ and $\mathbf{W}$ in \cref{eq:water_model} needs careful calibration; weak coupling may limit optimization gains.
    \item \textbf{Computational Scalability:} The joint optimization is NP-hard; heuristic solutions may be necessary for very large-scale deployments.
    \item \textbf{Sensor Heterogeneity:} Integrating different sensor types (optical, chemical) with varying costs, accuracies, and lifespans adds complexity to the optimization.
\end{itemize}

\section{Conclusion and Future Work}\label{sec:conclusion}
We have presented a unified geo-ecological information-modeling system for the coupled monitoring of photon concentration (light pollution) and water quality. The framework integrates a novel photon concentration module, a coupled prediction model, and a joint optimization engine within the established \gims architecture. This integration enables the treatment of \alan as a standard atmospheric pollutant and optimizes sparse sensor networks for monitoring multiple interacting stressors.

The key contributions are:
\begin{enumerate}
    \item The mathematical formulation for embedding photon concentration conversion into environmental monitoring systems.
    \item A joint optimization objective for multi-pollutant sensor network design.
    \item A detailed experimental plan for validating the framework's efficacy and efficiency.
\end{enumerate}

Future work will focus on:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Real-world Deployment:} Implementing the system in a testbed coastal lagoon with dedicated dual-purpose sensor stations.
    \item \textbf{Enhanced Coupling Models:} Developing process-based models for light-water interactions (e.g., photochemical reactions, biological rhythms).
    \item \textbf{Multi-fidelity Optimization:} Incorporating lower-cost proxy measurements (e.g., satellite data, citizen science observations) into the optimization framework.
    \item \textbf{Extended Pollutant Classes:} Incorporating additional pollutants (e.g., noise, microplastics) into the unified optimization paradigm.
\end{itemize}

By providing a unified, physically-grounded, and adaptive monitoring framework, this work aims to advance the management of anthropogenic impacts on complex ecological systems.

